postcontent:
I have a CMMG (Central Missouri Machine Gun, www.cmmginc.com) AR-15 for sale.  I purchased the upper in Jan 2010, the lower in Feb 2010. It comes with 2 Magpul 20-round Pmags, UTG 1-4X24 long eye relief CQB scope with illuminated mil-dot range estimating reticle, Magpul MBUS folding rear sight with dual apertures, ambidextrous single point sling, and a tactical rifle case from MidwayUSA. 
Specifications:
16” chrome lined barrel and chamber, 1:7 twist, M4 profile, 4150 steel, Magnetic Particle tested, with M4 feed ramp extensions
5.56 NATO chamber
Shot peened, Magnetic Particle tested bolt with full auto carrier

Midlength gas system
F Marked Front Sight Base
Round Forward Assist 
Standard M4 Handguard
Milspec buffer tube

6 position collapsible stock
While doing research on which AR to purchase I came upon a thread in forums.officer.com entitled ‘So you want to buy an AR-15, huh?’ and from which I learned a great deal about the AR-15 platform.  This thread is still active and the author (a police officer in Texas) chose the very rifle I have for sale as his choice to take into harm’s way.  His analysis of the features, specifications and reliability led him to choose CMMG over other brands because it was as reliable, priced better, and carried excellent product support.
In my experience this rifle has been perfect.  Whatever I have loaded it with, whether factory or handloads, has ALWAYS fed, fired, and ejected without any issues.  The 1:7 twist barrel will stabilize any weight bullet I choose, from the standard 55 grain commercial load up to 80 grain hunting bullets.  In fact, the bullet weight is only limited by overall length of the cartridges fitting in the magazine.
The scope is set in front of the rear sight on a ½” offset riser to provide optimum co-witness with the iron sights. Dial it back to 1x and it behaves like a red dot optic, zoom it up for longer shots. The reticle allows range estimation using the dots, which are 1 mil center to center.  The scope has QD rings.
This rifle will do all you want and more.  I am offering at $1800.

title: For Sale:  Remington New Model Army .44 Revolver (Authentic)
postcontent:
I have what appears to be an authentic Remington New Model Army .44 Revolver.  It is a friend of the families and was to have sat in a case in a closet for 40 some years. I took it to a gunsmith and he believes it is an original that has been refinished and a modification.  Under the trigger guard they have replaced a wire with a spring, I am not too familiar with the gun workings but apparently that is a modification.  The pictures I have are not showing the detail I would like, but I will do my best to describe it.  Across the top of the barrel there is this inscription, "Patented Sept. 14, 1858", then below that, "E. Remington and Sons, (something I cant read) then, New York U.S.A", then below that, "New Model".  The "New Model" is very hard to see.  The serial number is 101718 and is on the underside of the barrel.  The inspector stamps are D, R and M on the left side and W's on the right.  The cylinder marks are R and D.  There is also the serial number 101718 under the walnut stock.  There is also a worn inscription on the left walnut stock that I cannot make out.  I also took this gun to a gunshop and they too believe it is authentic.  Mechanically, the gun is in superb condition. I am guessing someone put some time into restoring it around the mid 1900's.  Due to the serial number, I am guessing this gun was manufactured around 1870.  Please do your due diligence regarding this gun and its authenticity.  I am selling it for a family friend and am in no way an expert in guns.  The information I provided is what what was told to me.  I am sorry about the poor picture quality.  Asking $1,500
REDACTED
I recieved a call from the gunsmith and the inscription on the left walnut stock is "OWA".  This was OW Ainsworth who was the final inspector for the Calvary model back then.  The civilian models did not have this stamp on the stock.

title: For Sale:  Browning Hi Power 9mm vintage collectable shooter
postcontent:
This is a Browning Hi Power 9mm, manufactured in Belgium in 1977.
It includes adjustable sites and the original collectible gun case and one 13 round magazine.
It is in great condition with the only defect I can identify is a slight blemish in the bluing on the top of the slide.
I believe that I am the second owner. I've fired about 25 rounds. I was told the first owner, a collector, probably fired less than 100.
I will consider trades.

Note: the flash from the camera has caused the finish to look funky in a number of places. It is just an artifact of the flash, don't be concerned.

Hi Power. Take a true classic to the range.
When it was introduced early in the 20th century, the Browning Hi Power 9mm pistol was a revelation. It offered the perfect balance of handling, size and firepower, with an impressive 13-round magazine capacity. Over the years, the Hi Power has aged gracefully and continues to have a loyal following among those “in the know.” Whether you are a novice or a seasoned shooter, you will appreciate the fine craftsmanship and function of these classic pistols, the sure heft of the machined steel frame and slide, and their natural pointability. Even with the double-column magazine, the grip is narrow to neatly accommodate nearly every hand size, and the single-action trigger provides a smooth, consistent pull. As reliable, accurate and easy to shoot as ever. Sure, there are many, many  other full-size 9mm pistols on the market that are made to meet many different requirements. But in the end, every true firearm enthusiast should have a Hi Power in their collection. Having and shooting the best just means something.
